ll="#c8922a" opacity="0.55"/><circle cx="150" cy="17" r="1.8" fill="#ffe090" opacity="0.4"/><circle cx="250" cy="18" r="4" fill="#c8922a" opacity="0.5"/><circle cx="250" cy="17" r="1.5" fill="#ffe090" opacity="0.35"/></svg>

You've come-to in a cubicle, in what you think is the Gents toilet in the Coach and Horses.

You gather your limbs to the bar.

The place is empty except for Jeffrey Bernard and, tall under the optics, his cow.

'You don't look well,' he says. 'Have you seen my cow?'

You heft your eyes to admire it, as he desires. He seems, for a moment, confused, then, owling his head in the direction you're looking, cries, 'There she is!'

She moos; he drinks.

'And I don't want that book you've got, either. Speak to Lackland, he'll be about. You best find your own way out.'
