:: His round {"position":"300,850","size":"100,100"}
<svg class="french-rule" viewBox="0 0 300 24" width="100%" height="24" preserveAspectRatio="none"><defs><linearGradient id="frC" x1="0" x2="1"><stop offset="0%" stop-color="#c8a86a" stop-opacity="0"/><stop offset="45%" stop-color="#c8a86a" stop-opacity="0.55"/><stop offset="100%" stop-color="#c8a86a" stop-opacity="0"/></linearGradient><linearGradient id="frD" x1="0" x2="1"><stop offset="0%" stop-color="#c8a86a" stop-opacity="0"/><stop offset="45%" stop-color="#c8a86a" stop-opacity="0.28"/><stop offset="100%" stop-color="#c8a86a" stop-opacity="0"/></linearGradient></defs><line x1="0" y1="7" x2="300" y2="7" stroke="url(#frD)" stroke-width="0.5"/><line x1="0" y1="12" x2="300" y2="12" stroke="url(#frC)" stroke-width="1.2"/><svg x="140" y="0" width="20" height="24" viewBox="-12 -2 24 26" preserveAspectRatio="xMidYMid meet"><g fill="#c8a86a" opacity="0.75"><path d="M0,15 C-3,10 -4,2 0,-1 C4,2 3,10 0,15Z"/><path d="M-1,13 C-4,10 -8,5 -9,3 C-9,5 -8,6 -6,5 C-3,8 -1,11 0,13Z"/><path d="M1,13 C4,10 8,5 9,3 C9,5 8,6 6,5 C3,8 1,11 0,13Z"/><rect x="-8" y="14" width="16" height="2.5" rx="0.5"/><ellipse cx="0" cy="20" rx="2.5" ry="2"/></g></svg></svg>

(set: $sobriety to $sobriety - 12)\
You nod; he orders two double whisky-sodas.

Clocking first, his face, then your own in a pier glass behind him, you observe that you both look much older than you should, had you aged normally or healthily in the time since you stopped speaking.

His slate eyes shine like slate does after cold rain.

'You're selling something,' he says. 'I saw you buttering Red.'

John St. John (for that is his name) is a poet who hates Red, with a hatred more instinct than reason. It took seed in the days when they both used the upstairs room in a Bloomsbury pub as their personal office, though its roots find life in something deeper.

(link: "⟡ LORE: On Red and John St. John ⟡")[<div class="lore-box"><p>There is a cleaving-apart in English poetics, much as there is in philosophy, which derives from a difference of opinion about the French and the Germans. Where Red isn't English, he is mostly French. He is Arthur Rimbaud on Charing Cross Road and his poems enact their dérive among the fragments of Mallarmé and Laforgue that Eliot shored up against the ruins in which the Great War left Europe.</p>

<p>In //Socialism: Utopian and Scientific// (1880), Friedrich Engels differentiates between socialists for whom socialism is mostly about acting to make the world better for those who live in it, who are often English, and those whose socialism is rooted in a scientific understanding of 'will', as an abstract, impersonal force, subject to the laws of dialectics, not Christian morality.</p>

<p>Red doesn't know it, but he is of the scientific party. John St. John, on the other hand, is an English poet, in the way that the Coverdale Bible is an English Bible.</p></div>]
<svg class="french-rule" viewBox="0 0 300 24" width="100%" height="24" preserveAspectRatio="none"><defs><linearGradient id="frC" x1="0" x2="1"><stop offset="0%" stop-color="#c8a86a" stop-opacity="0"/><stop offset="45%" stop-color="#c8a86a" stop-opacity="0.55"/><stop offset="100%" stop-color="#c8a86a" stop-opacity="0"/></linearGradient><linearGradient id="frD" x1="0" x2="1"><stop offset="0%" stop-color="#c8a86a" stop-opacity="0"/><stop offset="45%" stop-color="#c8a86a" stop-opacity="0.28"/><stop offset="100%" stop-color="#c8a86a" stop-opacity="0"/></linearGradient></defs><line x1="0" y1="7" x2="300" y2="7" stroke="url(#frD)" stroke-width="0.5"/><line x1="0" y1="12" x2="300" y2="12" stroke="url(#frC)" stroke-width="1.2"/><svg x="140" y="0" width="20" height="24" viewBox="-12 -2 24 26" preserveAspectRatio="xMidYMid meet"><g fill="#c8a86a" opacity="0.75"><path d="M0,15 C-3,10 -4,2 0,-1 C4,2 3,10 0,15Z"/><path d="M-1,13 C-4,10 -8,5 -9,3 C-9,5 -8,6 -6,5 C-3,8 -1,11 0,13Z"/><path d="M1,13 C4,10 8,5 9,3 C9,5 8,6 6,5 C3,8 1,11 0,13Z"/><rect x="-8" y="14" width="16" height="2.5" rx="0.5"/><ellipse cx="0" cy="20" rx="2.5" ry="2"/></g></svg></svg>
[[Drink with him|The Empty Glass]]

:: The Empty Glass {"position":"300,950","size":"100,100"}
<svg class="french-rule" viewBox="0 0 300 24" width="100%" height="24" preserveAspectRatio="none"><defs><linearGradient id="frC" x1="0" x2="1"><stop offset="0%" stop-color="#c8a86a" stop-opacity="0"/><stop offset="45%" stop-color="#c8a86a" stop-opacity="0.55"/><stop offset="100%" stop-color="#c8a86a" stop-opacity="0"/></linearGradient><linearGradient id="frD" x1="0" x2="1"><stop offset="0%" stop-color="#c8a86a" stop-opacity="0"/><stop offset="45%" stop-color="#c8a86a" stop-opacity="0.28"/><stop offset="100%" stop-color="#c8a86a" stop-opacity="0"/></linearGradient></defs><line x1="0" y1="7" x2="300" y2="7" stroke="url(#frD)" stroke-width="0.5"/><line x1="0" y1="12" x2="300" y2="12" stroke="url(#frC)" stroke-width="1.2"/><svg x="140" y="0" width="20" height="24" viewBox="-12 -2 24 26" preserveAspectRatio="xMidYMid meet"><g fill="#c8a86a" opacity="0.75"><path d="M0,15 C-3,10 -4,2 0,-1 C4,2 3,10 0,15Z"/><path d="M-1,13 C-4,10 -8,5 -9,3 C-9,5 -8,6 -6,5 C-3,8 -1,11 0,13Z"/><path d="M1,13 C4,10 8,5 9,3 C9,5 8,6 6,5 C3,8 1,11 0,13Z"/><rect x="-8" y="14" width="16" height="2.5" rx="0.5"/><ellipse cx="0" cy="20" rx="2.5" ry="2"/></g></svg></svg>
After these thoughts you drink and while you drink you notice that John's glass is empty already.

He drops it and it smashes.

'Thank God, that was empty,' he says, and stands.

You reach for your wallet and he waves you off.

'Next time,' he says, 'It all comes out in the wash.'

He's gone and you know that you owe something now. The fact of kindness ties you to this place.

