e-width="1"/><circle cx="22" cy="780" r="12" fill="url(#tnaB2)"/><circle cx="540" cy="820" r="9" fill="url(#tnaB1)"/><circle cx="35" cy="950" r="11" fill="url(#tnaB2)"/><circle cx="530" cy="1020" r="8" fill="url(#tnaB1)"/><circle cx="18" cy="1120" r="13" fill="url(#tnaB2)"/><circle cx="545" cy="1180" r="10" fill="url(#tnaB1)"/><circle cx="28" cy="1300" r="11" fill="url(#tnaB2)"/><ellipse cx="542" cy="880" rx="4" ry="15" transform="rotate(-8,542,880)" fill="rgba(68,32,7,0.38)"/><ellipse cx="20" cy="1060" rx="3" ry="12" transform="rotate(6,20,1060)" fill="rgba(68,32,7,0.35)"/><circle cx="58" cy="768" r="3" fill="rgba(132,80,28,0.21)"/><circle cx="518" cy="800" r="2.5" fill="rgba(124,74,22,0.19)"/><circle cx="44" cy="842" r="2" fill="rgba(138,84,30,0.18)"/><circle cx="534" cy="912" r="3.5" fill="rgba(128,76,24,0.22)"/><circle cx="26" cy="888" r="2" fill="rgba(142,88,32,0.17)"/><circle cx="548" cy="968" r="2" fill="rgba(122,70,20,0.20)"/><circle cx="66" cy="1000" r="3" fill="rgba(136,82,28,0.19)"/><circle cx="16" cy="1042" r="2.5" fill="rgba(130,78,26,0.18)"/><circle cx="524" cy="1080" r="4" fill="rgba(138,82,30,0.21)"/><circle cx="42" cy="1148" r="2" fill="rgba(124,74,22,0.17)"/><circle cx="538" cy="1220" r="3" fill="rgba(132,80,28,0.20)"/><circle cx="30" cy="1268" r="2.5" fill="rgba(140,86,30,0.19)"/><circle cx="520" cy="1340" r="3.5" fill="rgba(126,76,24,0.21)"/><circle cx="54" cy="1380" r="2" fill="rgba(134,82,28,0.17)"/><line x1="0" y1="900" x2="1000" y2="900" stroke="rgba(155,125,70,0.09)" stroke-width="1.5"/><line x1="0" y1="898" x2="1000" y2="898" stroke="rgba(75,50,20,0.05)" stroke-width="0.8"/></svg>
Autumn, 1973.

Soho, London.

You've written a book and you've a baby at home; tonight, somehow, you'll make them both make sense.

The book took much longer to make than the little girl, but after an immediate, impromptu effort, you can't take much credit for her anyway.

She is born now and her mother, Aoife, sits at home, with the babe in her arms.

Home's cold; at home there is not enough food. If she's told you once, she's told you again that there's not enough money coming in. You're a good man so you've taken a job in a warehouse by the flat. But you'll not make enough, not all year.

And so tonight, you've gone back to Soho, with a book in your bag and a sense of the place as it was, ten years ago, when //no wife, no house or land still seemed quite natural.//

You'll try, you suppose, the haunts you used to haunt and the people you knew. That'll work: it's a good book and God's a good man.

You've been thinking about the form of the aubade, the morning poem, the song of wake-me-not-so-I-might-have-my-dream. You've been thinking about the first love of your life; Lily, from the deepest valley in Wales.

<blockquote class="flash-reveal" style="margin:1em 0 0 2.5em;padding:0;border:none;">''Forget about your book, an aubade is a song to the dawn, and the only way out of Soho is to find one.''

[[NAME YOUR BOOK|Name Your Book]]</blockquote>
</div>

